File: The Supreme Court of Appeal has declared parts of the Marriage and Divorce acts unconstitutional. Flickr.com/Azlan DuPree JOHANNESBURG - The Supreme Court of Appeal has upheld a ruling that Muslim marriages be legally recognised.
It's declared parts of the Marriage and Divorce acts unconstitutional. Several organisations took government to court, seeking legal protection for women in Muslim marriages and their children. READ: SA Lockdown: Muslim council slams police conduct The Western High Court ruled in their favour in 2018 but the president and the justice minister appealed the ruling. Their bid has been dismissed and they have been ordered to pay the costs. Parliament now has 24 months to make corrections. The Constitutional Court will now have to confirm SCA's judgment.